The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, April 03, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, April 2: Silver prices zoomed to end at a record high of Rs 12,270 per kilo on the bullion market today due to hectic buying following a steep rise in the overseas prices. Ready silver (.999 fineness) opened at a new high of Rs 12,035 and continued to zoom before closing at Rs 12,270, a Rs-430 rise over the previous close of Rs 11,840. Standard gold (99.5 purity), opened at Rs 6,100, improved on increased support and closed at Rs 6,105, a gain of Rs 30 over Thursdays close of Rs 6,075.																								 New Delhi, April 2: The finance ministry today announced the sale of 6.18 per cent government stock, 2005 under the market stabilisation scheme for a notified amount of Rs 5,000 crore. The government stock will be sold by the Reserve Banks Mumbai office on Tuesday through a price-based auction using the multiple-price method.																								 Bangalore, April 2: The income tax department has served a Rs 261.4 crore demand notice to Wipro pertaining to its software profits. But Wipro said today that it would file an appeal against it.																								 Mumbai, April 2: The Reserve Bank today said that the offshore banking units in special economic zones will not be permitted to open foreign currency accounts of residents.																								 New Delhi, April 2: Cobra, the UK-based beer brand, has been relaunched in the country in collaboration with the Mount Shivalik group.
